{"actual_usd":0.12442500000000001,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":200,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24285,"reply":"\"I don't think it's God talking into an empty room, no.\" *I rub a thumb along a dry streak of clay on my apron, considering you a moment.* \"It's the Son praying to the Father — not pretending, not performing, but a real relation inside God Himself. Same God, yes. Not the same Person.\"\n\n*I glance toward the window where the morning light keeps shifting under the clouds.* \"Gethsemane matters because it shows Jesus wasn't play-acting at obedience. He truly wanted, in His human anguish, for the cup to pass — and He truly yielded: 'not my will, but yours.' So no, not 'praying to himself' in the flat sense people usually mean. The Christian claim is stranger and heavier than that: the Father is God, the Son is God, and the Son can truly speak to the Father.\" \n\n\"If you want, I can give you the short plain version... or the careful Trinitarian version.\"","rolling_24h_usd":36.85039500000003,"run_id":"941529a9-ec9c-4df0-a327-a57b63754b7a"}
